<article>
    <h1>An&#xAD;other di&#xAD;rec&#xAD;tor quits Ax&#xAD;ing&#xAD;ton board; two new in&#xAD;de&#xAD;pen&#xAD;dent di&#xAD;rec&#xAD;tors ap&#xAD;pointed</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201121/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-21"><time>2020-11-21</time></a>
        - <span>BUSINESS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>A re-des­ig­na­tion, a res­ig­na­tion, and two new ap­point­ments have re­shaped the board of Catal­istlisted Ax­ing­ton, which has seen tu­mult since cousins Nel­son and Ter­ence Loh be­came con­trol­ling share­hold­ers ear­lier this year.</p>
    <p>The changes, an­nounced yes­ter­day, took ef­fect on the same day.</p>
    <p>The res­ig­na­tion of five di­rec­tors in Au­gust left Ax­ing­ton with a two-mem­ber board.</p>
    <p>Of these two, in­de­pen­dent di­rec­tor Roberto Dona has been re-des­ig­nated non-ex­ec­u­tive chair­man, and will be ap­pointed a mem­ber of the remunerati­on com­mit­tee.</p>
    <p>In­de­pen­dent di­rec­tor and remunerati­on com­mit­tee chair­man Low Jun­rui has re­signed “in or­der to fa­cil­i­tate board re­newal and fo­cus on pri­mary work com­mit­ments”, said Ax­ing­ton.</p>
    <p>He took up the board po­si­tion in July.</p>
    <p>Two new in­de­pen­dent di­rec­tors have been ap­pointed, tak­ing the to­tal board mem­ber­ship up to three. All three board mem­bers will be on the remunerati­on, nom­i­nat­ing, and au­dit com­mit­tees.</p>
    <p>They are Mr Teo Choon Kow, also known as Wil­liam Teo, who will also be ap­pointed chair­man of the remunerati­on com­mit­tee, and Mr Ang Chi­ang Meng, who will also be ap­pointed chair­man of the au­dit com­mit­tee.</p>
    <p>Mr Teo, 73, re­tired in 2004 and has since been “fo­cus­ing on his in­de­pen­dent di­rec­tor­ships in Sin­ga­pore-listed com­pa­nies and on other com­mit­ments”.</p>
    <p>Mr Ang, 35, is a man­ag­ing part­ner in con­sult­ing firm Argile Part­ners, and was pre­vi­ously a re­struc­tur­ing pro­fes­sional with Borrelli Walsh.</p>


</article>

